ssdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || 1964<ref>{{cite web |title=Disused Stations:Blyth Station (2nd) |url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/b/blyth_second/index.shtml |website=www.disused-stations.org.uk |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || A [[Blyth and Tyne Railway#2019-present: Revised plans and the Northumberland Line project|proposal]] to reopen the freight-only [[Blyth and Tyne Railway]] to passengers has been mooted by SENRUG (South East Northumberland Rail User Group) and [[Northumberland County Council]]. If the line does reopen, a station would be built at {{rws|Newsham}} (south west of Blyth) as the former Blyth Branch is not part of the reopening plans.<ref name=\"TRM\">{{cite magazine|last=Pickering |first=Graeme |title=New targets for Northumberland |magazine=Rail Magazine |date=6 November 2019 |issue=891 |page=46 |publisher=Bauer Media |location=Peterborough |issn=0953-4563}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Dunstable]] || 36,253<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E04011941|title=Dunstable Parish|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || 1965<ref>{{cite web |title=Disused Stations: Dunstable Town Station |url=http://www.disused-stations.org.uk/d/dunstable_town/index.shtml |website=www.disused-stations.org.uk |accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> ||\n|-\n| [[Coalville]] || 34,575<ref>{{NOMIS2011|id=E35000934|title=Coalville Built-up area sub division|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> || 1964<ref>{{cite web |last1=Quick |first1=Michael |title=Railway Passenger Stations in England, Scotland and Wales; a Chronology |url=https://rchs.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/Railway-Passenger-Stations-v5.01-2.pdf |website=rchs.org.uk |accessdate=10 April 2020 |page=123 |format=PDF |date=2019}}</ref> || Proposed for reopening on the line between {{rws|Burton on Trent}} and {{rws|Leicester}}.<ref name=\"RM\">{{cite magazine |last1=Pickering |first1=Graeme |title=Rail Reopening Schemes |magazine=The Railway Magazine |date=April 2020 |volume=166 |issue=1,429 |page=39 |publisher=Mortons Media |location=Horncastle |is